german.json:
[
  {
    "id": "de-001",
    "language": "german",
    "date": "1941-10-15",
    "from": "Gefreiter Hans Becker",
    "from_unit": "6th Infanterie-Division, Army Group Centre",
    "nation": "Germany",
    "to": "Family",
    "location_written": "Near Vyazma, Russia",
    "subject": "Letter from the Eastern Front",
    "excerpt": "The distances here are incomprehensible. We have marched further in the last weeks than I could have believed possible...",
    "context": "By October 1941, Army Group Centre was deep into Operation Typhoon, the German drive on Moscow. The encirclement battles of Vyazma and Bryansk had just concluded, trapping approximately 663,000 Soviet troops in the largest encirclement in military history. German soldiers were advancing in autumn mud — the notorious Rasputitsa — still wearing summer uniforms, with winter equipment far behind in the supply chain. The halt before Moscow in December 1941 would prove the eastern campaign's first strategic failure.",
    "full_text": "Dearest Family,\n\nI write to you from somewhere near Vyazma, where we have halted to consolidate. The distances here are incomprehensible — we have marched and ridden further in the last weeks than I could have believed possible. Russia is not like France. The land goes on without end, and the autumn mud has already begun. My boots have not been dry in a week.\n\nDespite all this, spirits remain high. The men around me are good soldiers and good comrades. We have seen hard fighting, but we believe in what we are doing. The encirclement battles have been enormous — tens of thousands of prisoners streaming westward, more than I can count.\n\nI hope Father's health is improving. Tell Mother her package arrived with the socks and the Lebkuchen — they were shared with the whole section and gone in minutes. Everyone sends their thanks.\n\nI cannot say when I will next write, but know that I think of home every day.\n\nYour Hans",
    "notes": "Gefreiter Becker was killed in action near Rzhev in January 1942. This letter was returned to his family after the war.",
    "archive_source": "Private family collection, donated 1960",
    "sources": [
      {
        "type": "primary",
        "ref": "Original letter, private family collection, donated to Bundesarchiv-Militärarchiv, Freiburg, 1960. Bestand RH 37/6254."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Glantz, David M. and House, Jonathan. When Titans Clashed: How the Red Army Stopped Hitler. University Press of Kansas, 1995."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Stahel, David. Operation Typhoon: Hitler's March on Moscow, October 1941. Cambridge University Press, 2013."
      }
    ],
    "related_records": [
      {
        "id": "de-002",
        "title": "Müller — Stalingrad Pocket (1942)",
        "type": "German Collection"
      },
      {
        "id": "de-004",
        "title": "Haas — Normandy (1944)",
        "type": "German Collection"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "de-002",
    "language": "german",
    "date": "1942-12-28",
    "from": "Unteroffizier Karl Müller",
    "from_unit": "6th Army, Stalingrad Pocket",
    "nation": "Germany",
    "to": "Wife",
    "location_written": "Stalingrad",
    "subject": "Final letter from the Stalingrad Pocket",
    "excerpt": "I no longer believe we will be relieved. The Manstein attempt has failed. I ask only that you remember me as I was in better days...",
    "context": "By late December 1942, approximately 290,000 German and Axis troops of the 6th Army were encircled at Stalingrad following Operation Uranus (November 1942). Operation Winter Storm — Field Marshal von Manstein's relief attempt — was halted on 23 December 1942 approximately 48 km from the pocket. Rations had been cut to 50 grams of bread per day. The Luftwaffe airlift was providing less than a quarter of the required daily supply tonnage. The men inside the pocket largely understood their situation. The last mail airlift left the pocket on 14 January 1943; the 6th Army surrendered on 2 February 1943.",
    "full_text": "My dear Helga,\n\nI write this knowing it may be my last letter. The situation is clear to every man here who is honest with himself — I no longer believe we will be relieved. The relief attempt has failed. The rations now are almost nothing; we burn furniture for warmth.\n\nI do not write this to cause you distress, but because I believe you deserve the truth from me. I have conducted myself with honour. I have not surrendered though I might have. I believe that counts for something.\n\nIf God wills that I do not return, please raise the children to know that their father loved them above all things. Do not teach them hatred. The world we were told we were fighting for has not come to pass.\n\nKiss the children for me. I see your face each night when I sleep.\n\nYour Karl",
    "notes": "Müller surrendered on 2 February 1943 and died in Soviet captivity in March 1943. This letter was part of the last mail airlift from the Stalingrad pocket.",
    "archive_source": "Bundesarchiv-Militärarchiv, Freiburg",
    "sources": [
      {
        "type": "primary",
        "ref": "Original letter, Bundesarchiv-Militärarchiv, Freiburg. Bestand MSg 2/2763. Part of the Letzte Briefe aus Stalingrad collection."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Beevor, Antony. Stalingrad. Viking, 1998.",
        "note": "Definitive English-language account of the battle and its human cost."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Last Letters from Stalingrad. Translated by Franz Schneider and Charles Gullans. William Morrow, 1962.",
        "note": "Collected correspondence from the airlift; provides direct comparison texts."
      }
    ],
    "related_records": [
      {
        "id": "de-001",
        "title": "Becker — Vyazma, Eastern Front (1941)",
        "type": "German Collection"
      },
      {
        "id": "de-003",
        "title": "Von Schiller — Paris (1940)",
        "type": "German Collection"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "de-003",
    "language": "german",
    "date": "1940-06-20",
    "from": "Oberleutnant Friedrich von Schiller",
    "from_unit": "3rd Panzer Division, France",
    "nation": "Germany",
    "to": "Father",
    "location_written": "Paris, France",
    "subject": "From Paris — after the victory",
    "excerpt": "Father, we drove into Paris this morning. The boulevards are empty and silent. I confess I felt something complicated standing beneath the Arc de Triomphe...",
    "context": "The Fall of France (May–June 1940) was one of the most shocking military collapses in modern history. The German Manstein Plan (Fall Gelb) sent armoured forces through the Ardennes, bypassing the Maginot Line and encircling Allied forces in Belgium. Paris was declared an open city on 13 June 1940; German forces entered on 14 June. France signed the Armistice on 22 June 1940 in the same railway carriage where Germany had signed the 1918 Armistice — a deliberate symbolic act by Hitler. For German officers of the old military class, the victory produced complex emotions: professional pride alongside unease about what it had been done in service of.",
    "full_text": "Dear Father,\n\nI write from Paris — it is still strange to write those words. We drove in this morning with the column; the boulevards are empty and largely silent. A few French civilians watch from shuttered windows. I confess I felt something complicated standing beneath the Arc de Triomphe in uniform. Greatness visited by greatness, perhaps, though I know that is not how they will see it.\n\nThe campaign was everything the training had promised and more. The Panzer felt like thunder rolling across the earth. The French were not cowards — they fought in places — but they could not adjust. We were always somewhere they did not expect.\n\nGeneral Rommel was remarkable. I saw his command vehicle once during the crossing of the Meuse. He was right at the front, watching the engineers. No hesitation.\n\nI hope we have seen the last of the fighting. Perhaps now a negotiated peace will be possible, and I can come home.\n\nYour Fritz",
    "notes": "Von Schiller survived the war and emigrated to Argentina in 1947.",
    "archive_source": "Private collection",
    "sources": [
      {
        "type": "primary",
        "ref": "Original letter, private collection. Photocopy held at Institut für Zeitgeschichte, Munich. ED 200/5."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Frieser, Karl-Heinz. The Blitzkrieg Legend: The 1940 Campaign in the West. Naval Institute Press, 2005.",
        "note": "Definitive operational history of the French campaign based on German archives."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Jackson, Julian. The Fall of France: The Nazi Invasion of 1940. Oxford University Press, 2003."
      }
    ],
    "related_records": [
      {
        "id": "de-002",
        "title": "Müller — Stalingrad Pocket (1942)",
        "type": "German Collection"
      },
      {
        "id": "de-004",
        "title": "Haas — Normandy (1944)",
        "type": "German Collection"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "de-004",
    "language": "german",
    "date": "1944-07-25",
    "from": "Hauptmann Werner Haas",
    "from_unit": "12th SS Panzer Division Hitlerjugend, Normandy",
    "nation": "Germany",
    "to": "Sister",
    "location_written": "Normandy, France",
    "subject": "After the invasion",
    "excerpt": "The weight of the Allied material is something no one here was prepared for. We hold our positions, but each attack costs us men we cannot replace...",
    "context": "The Normandy campaign (June–August 1944) saw the Wehrmacht attempting to hold back Allied forces following the D-Day landings of 6 June 1944. The 12th SS Panzer Division Hitlerjugend, composed largely of Hitler Youth volunteers aged 17–18 led by experienced Eastern Front veterans, fought in the Caen sector with extraordinary ferocity. Allied material superiority — particularly in artillery and air power — imposed catastrophic attrition on German armoured formations. By 25 July 1944, the day of this letter, Operation Cobra (the American breakout) was imminent. The Falaise Pocket in August 1944 would destroy much of the German force in Normandy.",
    "full_text": "Dear Lotte,\n\nI have little time to write, but I want you to know I am alive. The situation in Normandy is not what the radio describes. The weight of Allied material — tanks, artillery, aircraft above all — is something no one here was fully prepared for. We hold our positions, but each attack costs us men we cannot replace. The replacements when they come are boys.\n\nI will not write what I truly think of our chances. You will understand what my silence means.\n\nI ask only one thing: if anything happens to me, see that my books go to the university library in Freiburg. Father will know which ones.\n\nThink of me on Sundays.\n\nYour Werner",
    "notes": "Hauptmann Haas was wounded at Falaise in August 1944 and survived the war. He became a schoolteacher in Baden-Württemberg.",
    "archive_source": "Family donation, Bundesarchiv",
    "sources": [
      {
        "type": "primary",
        "ref": "Original letter, Bundesarchiv-Militärarchiv, Freiburg. Bestand MSg 1/3021. Family donation, 1972."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Hastings, Max. Overlord: D-Day and the Battle for Normandy. Simon & Schuster, 1984."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Meyer, Hubert. The History of the 12. SS-Panzerdivision 'Hitlerjugend'. J.J. Fedorowicz, 1994.",
        "note": "Unit history; use with awareness of author's participation in the events described."
      }
    ],
    "related_records": [
      {
        "id": "de-001",
        "title": "Becker — Eastern Front (1941)",
        "type": "German Collection"
      },
      {
        "id": "de-003",
        "title": "Von Schiller — Paris (1940)",
        "type": "German Collection"
      }
    ]
  }
]

italian.json:
[
  {
    "id": "it-001",
    "language": "italian",
    "date": "1942-11-10",
    "from": "Sergente Lorenzo Ferretti",
    "from_unit": "8th Army (ARMIR), Don River Front",
    "to": "Mother",
    "location_written": "Don River, Soviet Union",
    "subject": "Letter from the Don",
    "excerpt": "The Russian winter has arrived. We have equipment for autumn, not this. But we are Italians — we improvise, we survive...",
    "context": "By autumn 1942, the Italian 8th Army (ARMIR) held a 270-km sector of the Don River front as part of the Axis forces supporting the German thrust toward Stalingrad. The Italian forces were critically underequipped for the Soviet winter, lacking adequate winter clothing, anti-tank weapons, and artillery. The Soviet Operation Ostrogozhsk-Rossosh in January 1943 would shatter the 8th Army entirely.",
    "original_text": "Cara Mamma,\n\nL'inverno russo è arrivato ed è al di là di qualsiasi cosa avessi immaginato. Abbiamo equipaggiamento per l'autunno, non per questo freddo. I tedeschi sono meglio attrezzati, ma noi ce la caviamo. Siamo italiani — improvvisiamo, sopravviviamo, condividiamo quel poco che abbiamo.\n\nIl paese qui è piatto oltre ogni credere. La steppa si estende all'orizzonte in ogni direzione — nessuna collina, nessun albero, solo cielo ed erba gelata. È bella in modo terribile.\n\nI pacchi alimentari che hai mandato sono arrivati danneggiati ma ugualmente accolti con gratitudine. Il vino soprattutto — condiviso con tutta la mia sezione nella festa di San Martino, un piccolo calore in questo posto gelato.\n\nPrega per me. E per tutti noi qui.\n\nIl tuo Lorenzo",
    "translation": "Dear Mother,\n\nThe Russian winter has arrived and it is beyond anything I had imagined. We have equipment for autumn, not for this cold. The Germans are better equipped, but we manage. We are Italians — we improvise, we survive, we share what little we have.\n\nThe country here is flat beyond belief. The steppe extends to the horizon in every direction — no hills, no trees, just sky and frozen grass. It is beautiful in a terrible way.\n\nThe food packages you sent arrived damaged but still gratefully received. The wine most of all — shared with my whole section on the feast of San Martino, a small warmth in this frozen place.\n\nPray for me. And for all of us here.\n\nYour Lorenzo",
    "notes": "Ferretti was among the survivors of the destruction of the 8th Army during Operation Ostrogozhsk-Rossosh in January 1943. He walked over 600 km west in the winter retreat before reaching German lines.",
    "archive_source": "Archivio di Stato, Rome",
    "sources": [
      {
        "type": "primary",
        "ref": "Original letter, Archivio di Stato di Roma, Fondo ARMIR, b. 14.",
        "note": "Italian-language original; translation by VeteransLedger editorial staff."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Schlemmer, Thomas. Invasori, non vittime: La campagna italiana di Russia 1941–1943. Laterza, 2009."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Revelli, Nuto. La guerra dei poveri. Einaudi, 1962. (Collected testimonies of Italian soldiers on the Eastern Front.)"
      }
    ],
    "related_records": [
      {
        "id": "it-002",
        "title": "Colombo — El Alamein (1942)",
        "type": "Italian Collection"
      },
      {
        "id": "it-003",
        "title": "Esposito — Monte Cassino (1944)",
        "type": "Italian Collection"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "it-002",
    "language": "italian",
    "date": "1942-09-02",
    "from": "Tenente Mario Colombo",
    "from_unit": "Ariete Division, El Alamein",
    "to": "Wife",
    "location_written": "North Africa",
    "subject": "From the desert — before the battle",
    "excerpt": "The desert here is magnificent in the early morning, before the heat begins. Rommel is nearby — one sees his staff cars passing. We wait...",
    "context": "The Ariete Armoured Division was one of the most effective Italian formations in North Africa. By September 1942 the Axis forces had been halted at El Alamein after the failure of the First Battle of El Alamein. Both sides were preparing for the decisive engagement; the British launched Operation Lightfoot on 23 October 1942. The Ariete Division fought to virtual annihilation holding the southern flank at Alamein, earning respect from Rommel himself.",
    "original_text": "Carissima Sofia,\n\nTi scrivo dal deserto, che confesso di aver imparato ad amare in modo strano. Al mattino presto, prima che cominci il caldo, è magnifico — la luce sulla sabbia, il silenzio, il lontano azzurro del mare. Poi arriva mezzogiorno e si preferirebbe essere ovunque altro.\n\nIl quartier generale di Rommel non è lontano — si vedono le sue auto dello stato maggiore sulla strada costiera, che lasciano polvere. Gli uomini lo rispettano, anche se è tedesco. Combatte fianco a fianco con i suoi uomini.\n\nCi hanno detto che un'offensiva britannica sta arrivando. Saremo pronti. La Divisione Ariete non si è mai ritirata quando poteva avanzare, e non intendiamo cominciare adesso.\n\nPenso a te e ai bambini ogni sera. Tieni la fotografia che ti ho mandato sul caminetto — quella in uniforme, non quella sciocca dalla spiaggia.\n\nTutto il mio amore, Mario",
    "translation": "Dearest Sofia,\n\nI write to you from the desert, which I confess I have grown to love in a strange way. In the early morning, before the heat begins, it is magnificent — the light on the sand, the silence, the distant blue of the sea. Then comes midday and one would rather be anywhere else.\n\nRommel's headquarters are not far — one sees his staff cars on the coastal road, trailing dust. The men respect him, even though he is German. He fights alongside his men.\n\nWe have been told a British offensive is coming. We will be ready. The Ariete Division has never retreated when it could advance, and we do not intend to start.\n\nI think of you and the children every evening. Keep the photograph I sent on the mantle — the one in uniform, not the silly one from the beach.\n\nAll my love, Mario",
    "notes": "Tenente Colombo was killed at El Alamein on 24 October 1942, the first day of the Second Battle of El Alamein. The Ariete Division held its positions until nearly all its tanks and most of its men had been lost.",
    "archive_source": "Private family collection",
    "sources": [
      {
        "type": "primary",
        "ref": "Original letter, private family collection, donated to the Museo della Battaglia di El Alamein, 1978."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Playfair, I.S.O. The Mediterranean and Middle East, Vol. IV. HMSO, 1966.",
        "note": "British official history covering the El Alamein battles."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Caccia Dominioni, Paolo. Alamein 1933–1962: An Account. George Allen & Unwin, 1966."
      }
    ],
    "related_records": [
