  {
    "id": "it-003",
    "language": "italian",
    "date": "1944-02-08",
    "from": "Caporale Vincenzo Esposito",
    "from_unit": "1st Parachute Division, Gustav Line",
    "to": "Father",
    "location_written": "Monte Cassino, Italy",
    "subject": "From the monastery hill",
    "excerpt": "Father, we are in a position that has no name yet on any map. The monastery above us watches everything. We cannot move by day without being seen...",
    "context": "The Battle of Monte Cassino (January–May 1944) was one of the bloodiest engagements of the Italian campaign. The Abbey of Monte Cassino stood at the centre of the German Gustav Line. German paratroopers of the 1st Parachute Division — elite soldiers — defended the hill with extraordinary tenacity against four Allied offensives. The abbey was controversially bombed by the Allies on 15 February 1944, an act that created better defensive ruins for the Germans. Cassino did not fall until 18 May 1944.",
    "original_text": "Caro Papà,\n\nTi scrivo da una posizione che non ha ancora nome su nessuna mappa. Il monastero sopra di noi osserva tutto. Non possiamo muoverci di giorno senza essere visti. I miei compagni e io viviamo come talpe nelle gallerie che abbiamo scavato nel tufo.\n\nI bombardamenti sono costanti. Arrivo a non sentirli più — è uno sfondo, come il vento. Ciò che mi preoccupa sono i silenzi, quando tutto si ferma e si sa che sta arrivando qualcosa.\n\nNon ho paura di morire, Papà. Ho paura di non aver vissuto abbastanza. Ho ventitré anni e ho visto più guerra di quanta qualsiasi uomo dovrebbe vedere.\n\nManda saluti alla Mamma. Dille che sto bene. Non è esattamente vero, ma è la cosa più gentile.\n\nVincenzo",
    "translation": "Dear Father,\n\nI write to you from a position that has no name yet on any map. The monastery above us watches everything. My comrades and I live like moles in the tunnels we have dug in the tufa.\n\nThe bombardments are constant. I have stopped hearing them — they are a background, like the wind. What worries me are the silences, when everything stops and you know that something is coming.\n\nI am not afraid of dying, Father. I am afraid of not having lived enough. I am twenty-three years old and I have seen more war than any man should see.\n\nSend my greetings to Mother. Tell her I am well. That is not exactly true, but it is the kindest thing.\n\nVincenzo",
    "notes": "Caporale Esposito survived the Battle of Monte Cassino and the subsequent retreat up the Italian peninsula. He was wounded near Bologna in April 1945 and was hospitalised when the war ended.",
    "archive_source": "Commissariato Generale Onoranze Caduti in Guerra, Rome",
    "sources": [
      {
        "type": "primary",
        "ref": "Original letter, Archivio della Famiglia Esposito, Napoli. Donated 1988."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Parker, Matthew. Monte Cassino. Headline, 2003.",
        "note": "Comprehensive account of the four battles."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Hapgood, David and Richardson, David. Monte Cassino. Congdon & Weed, 1984."
      }
    ],
    "related_records": [
