    "subject": "After Monte Cassino",
    "body": "Irena,\n\nWe took it. The monastery is ours — or what remains of it. They hoisted the Polish flag this morning at ten past ten. I was fifty metres away and I wept, which I am not ashamed to admit.\n\nI will not describe the battle itself, except to say that what happened on Phantom Ridge and Point 593 over the past weeks is beyond description. The New Zealanders and the Indians tried before us. The Americans and the French tried before them. It was left to us. Anders told us it would be — told us that we would show the world what Poles could do. We did.\n\nMy friend Bolek Wiśniewski was killed on the night of the 17th. He was from Lwów, as you know. His family have no home to return to now, any more than we have. That is the thing I cannot place — fighting for a land that is already lost before we have won.\n\nBut the flag is on the monastery. That is something they cannot take back.\n\nYour brother who loves you,\nStanek",
    "historical_context": "The 2nd Polish Corps under General Władysław Anders assaulted Monte Cassino on the night of 11–12 May 1944 as part of Operation Diadem. After savage fighting on the surrounding peaks, they captured the ruins of the monastery on 18 May 1944, raising the Polish regimental flag at 10:20. The II Corps had been formed largely from Poles released from Soviet labour camps under the Sikorski-Maisky agreement. Many soldiers like Kmiecik came from areas of eastern Poland (Lwów/Lviv) that were incorporated into the Soviet Union after the war — meaning that victory at Cassino could not be followed by a homecoming.",
