    "subject": "Forty-third day",
    "body": "I do not know who will read this. Perhaps no one.\n\nToday is the forty-third day of the Rising. We have not eaten properly in a week. There is water from a pump three streets away — we go at night, two at a time, with a cloth tied round the pail to stop it sloshing.\n\nThe sewers. I will not write about the sewers except to say that I understand now why the older men said nothing, only looked at one another, when the order came to use them.\n\nZbyszek was killed this morning. He was seventeen. He had a photograph of his mother and a volume of Norwid in his coat pocket. I am keeping the Norwid.\n\nThe planes came again from the East and circled. They did not drop anything. The radio says the Soviets have stopped. People say different things about why. I do not have an opinion any more. I only know what is here, in this street, in this hour.\n\nMy name is Hanna Czajkowska. I am twenty-three years old. I was a student of philology at the University of Warsaw before the war. I wanted to be a teacher.\n\nI want whoever finds this to know that we were real people. That we were here. That we chose to fight.\n\nH.",
    "historical_context": "The Warsaw Uprising began on 1 August 1944 (W-Hour, 17:00) and continued for 63 days until capitulation on 2 October. The letter's reference to Soviet aircraft circling without dropping supplies reflects the contested and deeply debated Soviet decision not to provide meaningful air support during the critical phase. The Home Army fought with captured and parachuted weapons; the sewers (kanały) were used for movement and communication between sectors. 'Danuta's' survival is not documented; approximately 200,000 Warsaw civilians died during the uprising and its aftermath. Norwid (Cyprian Kamil Norwid) was a 19th-century Polish Romantic poet widely read in the underground.",
