    "translator_note": "Translated from Polish. Letter passed through German censorship; certain passages may have been self-censored by the author. Original held at the Central Military Archive, Warsaw.",
    "subject": "From captivity — the fourth year",
    "body": "My dearest Zofia,\n\nThe Red Cross parcel arrived, eventually, though much reduced from what was originally sent. The Canadians in the next block are generous. We exchange language lessons — my English improves; their Polish remains, diplomatically, a work in progress.\n\nIt has been four years and four months since September. In that time I have read every book in the camp library twice. I have given lectures on the history of the Piast dynasty to whoever will attend. I have kept myself from despair by making a study of despair — its mechanisms, its relationship to hope, the difference between hope and delusion.\n\nThe news reaches us slowly and incompletely. We know that things are moving. One does not celebrate yet.\n\nI think about you constantly. I think about Karolina and whether she still remembers my face. She was three years old when I left. She is seven now. In my mind she is still three.\n\nI will come home. I believe this with the stubbornness that has kept me here. The world will be very different from the one I left. We will be very different from the people we were. But we will sit together in our kitchen with the samovar and we will know that we survived.\n\nYour Władek",
    "historical_context": "Oflag VII-A Murnau was an officer prisoner-of-war camp in Bavaria holding primarily Polish and later Allied officers. Major Szymański was among the Polish officers captured in the September 1939 campaign. The letter's careful language reflects awareness of German censorship. His reference to 'things moving' in January 1944 likely refers to the Allied advances in Italy and Soviet pressure in the East. The camp was liberated by the US Army in April 1945. Whether Major Szymański was reunited with his family in Warsaw — by 1945 devastated and under Soviet control — is not recorded.",
