    "language": "volunteers",
    "date": "1943-03-15",
    "from": "Sous-Lieutenant Jacques Dupont",
    "from_unit": "Légion des Volontaires Français (LVF), Eastern Front",
    "nation": "France",
    "to": "Father",
    "location_written": "Near Orel, Russia",
    "subject": "Letter from a French volunteer in Russia",
    "excerpt": "France has not ceased fighting. Here in Russia there are Frenchmen who have not accepted the armistice as the final verdict of history...",
    "context": "The Légion des Volontaires Français contre le Bolchevisme (LVF) was a French volunteer unit that fought on the Eastern Front under German command from 1941. Founded by French collaborationist politicians, it attracted approximately 13,400 volunteers over its existence. Ideologically anti-communist and often collaborationist, the LVF served in anti-partisan operations and frontline combat. It was later incorporated into the Waffen-SS as the 33rd Waffen Grenadier Division of the SS 'Charlemagne'. Many LVF veterans were among the last defenders of the Berlin bunker complex in April 1945.",
    "full_text": "Mon Père,\n\nJ'écris de quelque part près d'Orel, où nous tenons une ligne dans la boue du dégel de printemps. Les conditions sont horribles mais les hommes tiennent bon.\n\nTu m'as demandé pourquoi j'ai fait cela. Je vais essayer d'expliquer une fois encore. La France n'a pas cessé de se battre — ici en Russie, il y a des Français qui n'ont pas accepté l'armistice comme le verdict final de l'histoire. Nous nous battons contre le bolchevisme, que nous voyons comme la menace fondamentale de la civilisation européenne.\n\nSi l'Europe perd cette guerre à l'Est, tout perd sa signification. C'est ce que je crois. Tu peux appeler cela un mensonge que je me raconte. Peut-être. Mais j'ai besoin de quelque chose en quoi croire.\n\nDis à Maman que je mange bien et que ma santé est bonne. Ce n'est pas entièrement vrai, mais c'est ce qu'elle a besoin d'entendre.\n\nJacques",
    "translation": "My Father,\n\nI write from somewhere near Orel, where we hold a line in the mud of the spring thaw. The conditions are terrible but the men hold.\n\nYou have asked me why I did this. I will try to explain once more. France has not ceased fighting — here in Russia there are Frenchmen who have not accepted the armistice as the final verdict of history. We fight against Bolshevism, which we see as the fundamental threat to European civilisation.\n\nIf Europe loses this war in the East, everything loses meaning. This is what I believe. You may call it a lie I tell myself. Perhaps. But I need something to believe in.\n\nTell Mother that I am eating well and my health is good. That is not entirely true, but it is what she needs to hear.\n\nJacques",
    "notes": "Sous-Lieutenant Dupont survived the Eastern Front and served with the Charlemagne Division in the final defence of Berlin in April 1945. He surrendered to French forces, was tried for collaboration, and sentenced to twenty years' imprisonment. He was released in 1958 under a general amnesty.",
    "archive_source": "Service Historique de la Défense, Vincennes (France)",
